g. Moreover, after controlling for differences in VL and CD4 <sup>+</sup> T-cell count, genes within the type I IFN signaling pathway were further shown to be more highly expressed in women, whereas those genes more highly expressed in men showed no such enrichment. A subset of the genes highly expressed in women was further identified, including several involved in type I IFN signaling in response to viral infections ( <i>IRF7</i> , <i>DDX58</i> , <i>SAMHD1</i> , <i>OAS2</i> , and <i>TRIM14</i> ), that both are more highly expressed in CD4 <sup>+</sup> T cells from women and negatively correlated with VL, suggesting that they play a role in the comparative control of VL observed in women.</p><p style="color: lightgray"> PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39902043/?utm_source=Chrome&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=journals&utm_content=101560960&ff=20250204131345&v=2.18.0.post9+e462414">39902043</a> | PMC: <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/PMC11788160/?utm_source=Chrome&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=journals&utm_content=101560960&ff=20250204131345&v=2.18.0.post9+e462414">PMC11788160</a> | doi： <a href=https://doi.org/10.3389/fimmu.2024.1507530>10.3389/fimmu.2024.1507530</a></p></div> ]]>;</content:encoded><guid ispermalink="false"> pubmed:39902043</guid><pubDate> Tue, 04 Feb 2025 06:00:00 -0500</pubDate><dc:creator> Elina El-Badry</dc:creator><dc:creator> Luxiao Chen</dc:creator><dc:creator> Khader Ghneim</dc:creator><dc:creator> Ziyi li</dc:creator><dc:creator> Kelsie Brooks</dc:creator><dc:creator> Jake Rhodes</dc:creator><dc:creator> Rafick Sekaly</dc:creator><dc:creator> William Kilembe</dc:creator><dc:creator> Susan Allen</dc:creator><dc:creator> hao Wu</dc:creator><dc:creator>埃里克·亨特（Eric Hunter）</dc:creator><dc:date> 2025-02-04</dc:date><dc:source>免疫学领域</dc:source><dc:title>Heightened expression of type I interferon signaling genes in CD4&lt;sup>;+&lt;/sup>; T cells from acutely HIV-1-infected women is associated with lower viral loads</dc:title><dc:identifier> pmid:39902043</dc:identifier><dc:identifier> pmc:PMC11788160</dc:identifier><dc:identifier> doi:10.3389/fimmu.2024.1507530</dc:identifier></item><item><title> Lymphoma patients treated with anti-CD20 and chemotherapy display disconnected T and B cell responses to COVID-19 vaccine</title><link/> https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39902042/?utm_source=Chrome&amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;utm_campaign=journals&amp;utm_content=101560960&amp;fc=None&amp;ff=20250204131345&amp;v=2.18.0.post9+e462414<description> Due to immunosuppressive treatment, COVID-19 vaccination is challenging in patients with B-cell lymphoma. We prospectively evaluated CD4, CD8 T-cell and serological responses to the COVID-19 mRNA vaccine in a cohort of patients treated for a B-cell lymphoma with anti-CD20 therapy. During lymphoma treatment, CD4, CD8, and CD19 cell dropped. While functional-specific CD4 and CD8 T-cell responses to SARS-CoV-2 were unaffected, vaccination in patients on treatment induced low specific antibody... </description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<div><p style="color: #4aa564;"><b>前免疫</b>。 2025 Jan 20;15:1524813. doi: 10.3389/fimmu.2024.1524813.环保2024。</p><p><b>抽象的</b></p><p xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:p1="http://pubmed.gov/pub-one"> Due to immunosuppressive treatment, COVID-19 vaccination is challenging in patients with B-cell lymphoma. We prospectively evaluated CD4, CD8 T-cell and serological responses to the COVID-19 mRNA vaccine in a cohort of patients treated for a B-cell lymphoma with anti-CD20 therapy. During lymphoma treatment, CD4, CD8, and CD19 cell dropped. While functional-specific CD4 and CD8 T-cell responses to SARS-CoV-2 were unaffected, vaccination in patients on treatment induced low specific antibody titers, contrasting with a preserved serological response when vaccination was completed before treatment initiation. Those findings reinforce a vaccinal strategy based on completion before lymphoma treatment, with a booster administered afterward.</p><p style="color: lightgray"> PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39902042/?utm_source=Chrome&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=journals&utm_content=101560960&ff=20250204131345&v=2.18.0.post9+e462414">39902042</a> | PMC: <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/PMC11788169/?utm_source=Chrome&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=journals&utm_content=101560960&ff=20250204131345&v=2.18.0.post9+e462414">PMC11788169</a> | DOI: <a href=https://doi.org/10.3389/fimmu.2024.1524813>10.3389/fimmu.2024.1524813</a></p></div> ]]>;</content:encoded><guid ispermalink="false"> pubmed:39902042</guid><pubDate> Tue, 04 Feb 2025 06:00:00 -0500</pubDate><dc:creator> Sylvain Lamure</dc:creator><dc:creator> Houria Hendel Chavez</dc:creator><dc:creator> Marie-Ghislaine de Goër de Herve</dc:creator><dc:creator> Luc-Matthieu Fornecker</dc:creator><dc:creator> Bernard Drenou</dc:creator><dc:creator> Caroline Jacquet</dc:creator><dc:creator> Fatiha Merabet</dc:creator><dc:creator> Milena Kohn</dc:creator><dc:creator> Florence Quélin</dc:creator><dc:creator> Angela Jackson</dc:creator><dc:creator> Sylvain Choquet</dc:creator><dc:creator> Rémy Duléry</dc:creator><dc:creator> Yassine Taoufik</dc:creator><dc:creator> Caroline Besson</dc:creator><dc:date> 2025-02-04</dc:date><dc:source>免疫学领域</dc:source><dc:title>Lymphoma patients treated with anti-CD20 and chemotherapy display disconnected T and B cell responses to COVID-19 vaccine</dc:title><dc:identifier> pmid:39902042</dc:identifier><dc:identifier> pmc:PMC11788169</dc:identifier><dc:identifier> doi:10.3389/fimmu.2024.1524813</dc:identifier></item><item><title> &lt;em>;TLR10&lt;/em>; overexpression modulates immune response in A549 lung epithelial cells challenged with SARS-CoV-2 S and N proteins</title><link/> https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39902041/?utm_source=Chrome&amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;utm_campaign=journals&amp;utm_content=101560960&amp;fc=None&amp;ff=20250204131345&amp;v=2.18.0.post9+e462414<description> Toll-like receptors (TLRs) play an important role in the recognition of viral particles and activation of the innate immune system, but their role in SARS-CoV-2 infection is still poorly characterized. In the present study, we investigated the role of Toll-like receptor 10 (TLR10) in modulating the immune response during SARS-CoV-2 infection. The results showed that overexpression of TLR10 in A549 lung epithelial cells, immunostimulated with SARS-CoV-2 proteins S and N mainly downregulated... </description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<div><p style="color: #4aa564;"><b>前免疫</b>。 2025 Jan 20;15:1490478. doi: 10.3389/fimmu.2024.1490478.环保2024。</p><p><b>抽象的</b></p><p xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:p1="http://pubmed.gov/pub-one"> Toll-like receptors (TLRs) play an important role in the recognition of viral particles and activation of the innate immune system, but their role in SARS-CoV-2 infection is still poorly characterized. In the present study, we investigated the role of Toll-like receptor 10 (TLR10) in modulating the immune response during SARS-CoV-2 infection. The results showed that overexpression of <i>TLR10</i> in A549 lung epithelial cells, immunostimulated with SARS-CoV-2 proteins S and N mainly downregulated proinflammatory cytokines and interferons and affected gene expression in the cocultured THP-1 monocytes. Our results suggest that TLR10 could mediate the extent of SARS-CoV-2 infection by downregulating the release of inflammatory cytokines and chemokines such as <i>CXCL10</i> , <i>IL6</i> , <i>IL8</i> , and <i>IFNβ</i> . Modulation of <i>TLR10</i> expression could have implications for the treatment of patients with severe COVID-19, in whom excessive inflammation leading to the development of acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS) is a key feature. However, further research is needed to fully understand the impact of modulating <i>TLR10</i> expression on the antiviral response and the overall balance of the immune response during SARS-CoV-2 infection.</p><p style="color: lightgray"> PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39902041/?utm_source=Chrome&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=journals&utm_content=101560960&ff=20250204131345&v=2.18.0.post9+e462414">39902041</a> | PMC: <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/PMC11788150/?utm_source=Chrome&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=journals&utm_content=101560960&ff=20250204131345&v=2.18.0.post9+e462414">PMC11788150</a> | DOI: <a href=https://doi.org/10.3389/fimmu.2024.1490478>10.3389/fimmu.2024.1490478</a></p></div> ]]>;</content:encoded><guid ispermalink="false"> pubmed:39902041</guid><pubDate> Tue, 04 Feb 2025 06:00:00 -0500</pubDate><dc:creator> Špela Knez</dc:creator><dc:creator> Mojca Narat</dc:creator><dc:creator> Jernej Ogorevc</dc:creator><dc:date> 2025-02-04</dc:date><dc:source>免疫学领域</dc:source><dc:title>&lt;em>;TLR10&lt;/em>; overexpression modulates immune response in A549 lung epithelial cells challenged with SARS-CoV-2 S and N proteins</dc:title><dc:identifier> pmid:39902041</dc:identifier><dc:identifier> pmc:PMC11788150</dc:identifier><dc:identifier> doi:10.3389/fimmu.2024.1490478</dc:identifier></item><item><title> Effect of trace elements and nutrients on 21 autoimmune diseases: a Mendelian randomization study</title><link/> https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39902040/?utm_source=Chrome&amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;utm_campaign=journals&amp;utm_content=101560960&amp;fc=None&amp;ff=20250204131345&amp;v=2.18.0.post9+e462414<description>结论：单变量和多变量的孟德尔随机研究的发现支持微量元素，营养和自身免疫性疾病之间的因果关系。这些结果对于开发针对自身免疫性疾病的靶向预防和治疗策略具有重大临床意义。 </description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<div><p style="color: #4aa564;"><b>前免疫</b>。 2025 Jan 20;15:1462815. doi: 10.3389/fimmu.2024.1462815.环保2024。</p><p><b>抽象的</b></p><p xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:p1="http://pubmed.gov/pub-one">背景：许多临床研究观察到血清微量元素，营养和自身免疫性疾病之间存在密切的关系。但是，血清微量因素，营养和自身免疫性疾病之间是否存在遗传因果作用。 </p><p xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:p1="http://pubmed.gov/pub-one">目的：本研究旨在研究使用门德尔随机分组（MR）对血清微量元素和养分对21种自身免疫性疾病的因果作用。 </p><p xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:p1="http://pubmed.gov/pub-one">方法：暴露因子（血清痕量元素和维生素）的单核苷酸多态性是从已发表的英国生物银行数据库和全基因组关联研究（GWAS）公共数据库中获得的。结果GWAS数据来自Finngen数据库。 MR被用来探索9条痕​​量元素与6种维生素和自身免疫性疾病之间的因果关系。使用反方差加权方法（MR EGGER和加权中值方法）进行因果推理。随后，进行了异质性测试，水平多效性测试，MR-PRESSO测试和剩余分析进行敏感性分析，以评估研究结果的鲁棒性。最后，在IVW方法中具有统计学意义，并且在五个方法中具有一致的效应大小和优势比作为因果关系及其并发症具有因果关系的暴露因素。此外，还采用了多变量的孟德尔随机化来评估多种暴露因素对自身免疫性疾病的综合作用。 </p><p xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:p1="http://pubmed.gov/pub-one">结果：MR分析表明，痕量元素铜的水平升高与全身性红斑狼疮（SLE）的风险增加和溃疡性结肠炎的风险降低有关。 Carotene was found to have a negative causal relationship with adult-onset Still <b>&#39;</b> s disease (AOSD).铜和硒水平升高与自身免疫性甲状腺功能亢进症的风险增加有关。钙水平显示出与肿瘤多炎的风险的负因果关系。 MVMR的结果表明，硒可以独立影响与铜分开的自身免疫性甲状腺功能亢进症的风险。 </p><p xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:p1="http://pubmed.gov/pub-one">结论：单变量和多变量的孟德尔随机研究的发现支持微量元素，营养和自身免疫性疾病之间的因果关系。这些结果对于开发针对自身免疫性疾病的靶向预防和治疗策略具有重大临床意义。</p><p style="color: lightgray"> PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39902040/?utm_source=Chrome&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=journals&utm_content=101560960&ff=20250204131345&v=2.18.0.post9+e462414">39902040</a> | PMC: <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/PMC11788298/?utm_source=Chrome&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=journals&utm_content=101560960&ff=20250204131345&v=2.18.0.post9+e462414">PMC11788298</a> | doi： <a href=https://doi.org/10.3389/fimmu.2024.1462815>10.3389/fimmu.2024.1462815</a></p></div> ]]>;</content:encoded><guid ispermalink="false"> pubmed:39902040</guid><pubDate> Tue, 04 Feb 2025 06:00:00 -0500</pubDate><dc:creator> Ming-Jie Jia</dc:creator><dc:creator> Hua-Fang Yin</dc:creator><dc:creator> Ying-Chao Liang</dc:creator><dc:creator>冯江</dc:creator><dc:creator>Hui-Lin Li</dc:creator><dc:date> 2025-02-04</dc:date><dc:source>免疫学领域</dc:source><dc:title>Effect of trace elements and nutrients on 21 autoimmune diseases: a Mendelian randomization study</dc:title><dc:identifier> pmid:39902040</dc:identifier><dc:identifier> pmc:PMC11788298</dc:identifier><dc:identifier> doi:10.3389/fimmu.2024.1462815</dc:identifier></item></channel></rss>